  "Idea": "We propose Subspace-Aware Dynamic Routing (SADR), a novel framework for enhancing sentence representation by decomposing transformer layer outputs into semantically meaningful, sparse subspaces and dynamically routing across both depth and functional modality. Rather than treating each layer as a monolithic embedding source, SADR first applies a set of lightweight, differentiable projectors to extract orthogonal subspaces corresponding to distinct linguistic functions: (1) Syntactic Structure (capturing word order, dependency relations), (2) Lexical-Semantic Content (word meaning and similarity), (3) Compositional Reasoning (handling negation, quantifiers, scope), and (4) Discourse Role (identifying claims, premises, connectives). These projectors are initialized using insights from diagnostic probing but are refined end-to-end during training. At inference time, a dynamic router—conditioned on both task gradients and real-time linguistic signals (e.g., parse depth, presence of logical operators)—selects and reweights active subspaces across multiple layers. For example, a complex question like 'What didn’t John claim Mary would deny?' may activate the compositional reasoning subspace in intermediate layers and discourse role units in deeper ones, while suppressing redundant lexical channels. The final representation is a fused tensor constructed via gated summation over selected subspaces, enabling highly efficient, context-sensitive integration. Because SADR operates on decomposed subspaces rather than full vectors, it reduces representational redundancy and allows deeper models to be compressed post-hoc by pruning inactive pathways. Moreover, the modular design supports plug-in enhancements: new subspaces can be added (e.g., for emotion or formality) without retraining the entire model. By aligning architectural dynamics with cognitive processing principles—where humans recruit specialized subsystems depending on task demands—SADR moves beyond static depth-based hierarchies toward truly adaptive comprehension systems. Its impact spans improved performance on GLUE/SuperGLUE tasks (especially those requiring multi-step inference), enhanced model transparency (via subspace activation heatmaps), and reduced computational cost in deployment scenarios. Importantly, SADR can be applied atop frozen pre-trained transformers (e.g., BERT, DeBERTa) as an add-on module, offering a parameter-efficient way to boost performance without full fine-tuning.",
  "Title": "SADR: Subspace-Aware Dynamic Routing for Functional Decomposition and Adaptive Fusion in Transformer Representations",
  "Experiment": "The experimental pipeline consists of three stages. First, we implement SADR on BERT-base and RoBERTa-large, extracting hidden states from six evenly spaced layers. We define four initial subspace projectors as rank-16 linear transformations followed by sparsity-inducing penalties (e.g., L1 on projector weights) to encourage disentanglement. Each projector is pre-initialized using weights from simple probes trained to predict linguistic properties (e.g., dependency head count, negation span detection). During main training, these projectors are jointly optimized with a two-layer router network that takes as input: (a) aggregated linguistic signals (computed via spaCy/NLTK), and (b) task embedding (one-hot per GLUE task). The router outputs gating scores per (layer, subspace) pair, forming a 6x4 matrix of attention weights. Second, we evaluate on GLUE and SuperGLUE, comparing against strong baselines: standard [CLS], mean pooling, LiMSR, and AdaMix. We measure accuracy, calibration, and compute overhead. We particularly analyze gains on high-complexity subsets (e.g., MultiRC with long-range dependencies, BoolQ with negation). Third, we conduct extensive ablations: (i) removing subspace structure (flattening to full-layer routing), (ii) freezing projectors, (iii) replacing linguistic inputs with random noise, and (iv) measuring downstream transfer to low-data regimes (e.g., 100-shot SNLI). Ideal outcomes include: +1.0 average GLUE score improvement over LiMSR, interpretable routing patterns (e.g., high compositional gate values for MNLI), <5% increase in FLOPs, and robustness in few-shot settings due to better inductive biases.",
