  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework called Linguistically-Guided Multi-Scale Routing (LiMSR) for enhancing sentence representation in transformer models by adaptively combining embeddings from shallow and deep layers. Rather than relying on fixed aggregation strategies like summation or learned scalar weights, LiMSR introduces a differentiable router module that dynamically selects and reweights feature contributions from multiple transformer layers based on two inputs: (1) task-specific gradients derived from the downstream objective, and (2) interpretable linguistic signals extracted from the input sentence. These signals include syntactic depth (e.g., maximum depth in dependency parse trees), lexical diversity (e.g., type-token ratio within clauses), semantic compositionality (e.g., presence of negation or quantifiers), and discourse coherence cues (e.g., connective words). A lightweight probe network processes these features to generate gating coefficients that modulate a convex combination of layer-wise embeddings. Crucially, the router is trained end-to-end alongside the main model, allowing it to learn optimal trade-offs between representational fidelity and computational efficiency. For instance, sentences with complex syntax but simple semantics may receive higher weight from intermediate layers, while those involving abstract reasoning activate deeper layers more strongly. This creates a context- and task-aware representation pipeline that improves generalization across NLP benchmarks. The significance of LiMSR lies in its ability to unify insights from representation analysis, deep architecture design, and structured adaptation into a single, scalable framework. It enables transformers to behave more like adaptive cognitive systems—allocating processing resources where they are most needed—rather than applying uniform depth across all inputs. Potential impact includes improved performance on low-data regimes (due to better inductive biases), enhanced 